    "claim": "`liquidate()` does not enforce unique `users` entries and computes each slice's `borrowAmount` and `collateralShare` with floor rounding against the same pre-update `totalBorrow`, only reconciling aggregate totals once after the loop. Repeating the same insolvent account across many small `maxBorrowPart` entries accumulates round-down error, so more `borrowPart` can be cleared than the summed MIM payment and collateral seizure should allow.",
    "impact": "An insolvent borrower can self-liquidate in many tiny slices to retire debt while retaining excess collateral. The MIM shortfall per slice is dust-sized, but the collateral shortfall is up to almost one BentoBox share per slice, so the loss can become material when share value is high or the batch is large.",
    "paths": [
      "Borrower becomes insolvent",
      "Call `liquidate()` with the same borrower repeated many times and tiny `maxBorrowPart` values",
      "Each iteration rounds `borrowAmount`/`collateralShare` down before `totalBorrow` is updated at the end"
    ]
  },
